         <div type="edition" xml:lang="ocm-Latn">
<p>
<lb n="1"/>sarvvā<choice><unclear>k</unclear><unclear>ch</unclear></choice>ālakṣetraṁ
<lb n="2"/>ṅauk· laṅā kṣetraṁ 
</p>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus">
               <listApp>
                  <app loc="1">
                     <lem>sarvvākāla-</lem>
                     <rdg source="bib:Finot1904_01">sarvvaṁ kāla-</rdg>
<note>It is true that an <foreign>anusvāra</foreign> seems to be present on <foreign>rvvā</foreign> but no meaning is transparent is we assume a declined Sanskrit form <foreign>sarvvāṁ</foreign> (accusative singular feminine) before <foreign>kālakṣetraṁ</foreign>, unless we assume that the rather clear <foreign>ā</foreign> marker is an error.</note>
<!-- <note>Is the intended word <foreign>sarvvākāla</foreign>-</note>-->
                  </app>
               </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" resp="part:argr">
 	<p n="1">Field for everything unseasonable <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>sarva-akāla</foreign></supplied>.</p>
	<p n="2">Upper sesame field.</p>
         </div>
	<div type="translation" xml:lang="fra" source="bib:Finot1904_01">
 	<p>Tout le champ Kāla, le champ de sésame Ṅauk.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>In view of the problem of reading exposed in the apparatus, the interpretation of the meaning of the first line is very tentative. Even the identification of the language as Old Cham would have to be reconsidered if a reading like Finot's were given preference.</p>
         </div>
